For the purpose of illustration, Iâ€™m using a dotted line to denote cherry-picks. This dotted line doesnâ€™t really exist in the repo, but Iâ€™m drawing it to help express the chronology. (Eventually, Iâ€™ll stop drawing dotted lines, too.)
You have some common ancestor A, and in the commit, the line in question is the word apple. From that common ancestor, the two branches diverge: Commit F1 happens on the feature branch, and commit M1 happens on the master branch. These changes donâ€™t affect the line in question, so it still says apple. You then make some commit F2 in the feature branch that changes the line in question from apple to berry, and you cherry-pick commit F2 into the master branch as M2.
So far, nothing exciting is happening.
Time passes, more commits occur, and your commit graph looks like this:



